ce:section.ce:para:
In order to demonstrate the application potential of the method for detection of E. coli O157:H7 in real samples, we investigated the applicability of the detection procedure described in section 2.2 in spiked samples. The fluorescence intensity was increased gradually as the concentration of E. coli O157:H7 gradually increased from 2.5 × 101 to 2.5 × 106 CFU/mL (Fig. 5
                        ). The fitted linear equations were y = 0.09327x + 0.41918 (R2 = 0.98402, pure culture) and y = 0.10329x + 0.41826 (R2 = 0.9499, lettuce sample), respectively. The limit of detection (LOD) of the fluorescence assay was all 25 CFU/mL. In addition, in order to further explore the applicability of the proposed method, fluorescence assay was performed on two other samples (spiked juice and pool water). The LOD of the established assay was 25 CFU/mL in both juice and pool water samples, and it exhibited a good linear relationship ranging from 2.5 × 101 CFU/mL to 2.5 × 106 CFU/mL (Fig. S8). Table 1
                         summarized the previously reported biosensor-based methods developed for detecting E. coli O157:H7 in food. It could be seen that the established assay has higher sensitivity or wider detection range compared with the reported photoelectrochemical assay, chemiluminescence method, colorimetric assay and fluorescence assay, which was attributed the high affinity of MNPs@B–N/APBA for target bacteria and the ability of mAb@R-CDs@BONs-NH2 to amplify the fluorescence response signals.
